<h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

<p>The common framing is "OpenAI costs money, Llama is free." That is wrong in both directions. OpenAI fine-tuning charges per token against a predictable SLA. Llama fine-tuning costs GPU compute, your own time, and the operational overhead of managing training infrastructure. Neither is strictly cheaper — the right choice depends on your dataset size, iteration cadence, and team's infrastructure tolerance.</p>

<p>This guide breaks down the actual numbers for a typical fine-tuning run: 10,000 examples averaging 400 tokens each (4M training tokens total).</p>

<h2 id="real-cost">The Real Cost of "Free"</h2>

<p>Meta's Llama 3.1 70B weights are free to download and fine-tune. But running a full fine-tune on 4M tokens requires:</p>

<ul>
  <li>A GPU with enough VRAM to hold the model and optimizer states. At 70B parameters, QLoRA (4-bit quantized LoRA) is the practical baseline — you still need ~48GB VRAM minimum, meaning at least one A100 80GB or two A6000 48GB GPUs.</li>
  <li>Training time of roughly 3–6 hours on a single A100 for 4M tokens at 1–3 epochs.</li>
  <li>Your time: setting up the training stack (usually Axolotl, LLaMA-Factory, or torchtune), debugging CUDA OOM errors, writing the evaluation loop.</li>
</ul>

<p>Cloud GPU providers (RunPod, Vast.ai, Lambda Labs) charge $1.50–$2.50/hr for an A100 80GB. A 5-hour run costs $7–12. That is cheap — but the figure assumes your first run succeeds. In practice, fine-tuning iterations include at least 2–3 failed runs before converging on good hyperparameters.</p>

