<p>The crossover point where Llama starts winning on raw economics is around 20+ training runs. A single fine-tuning job favours OpenAI on total cost including engineering time. A team running weekly fine-tune iterations against a growing dataset favours Llama at scale.</p>

<h2 id="formats">JSONL Formats</h2>

<p>This is the good news: both GPT-4.1 and Llama 3.1 use the same ChatML format with a <code>messages</code> array. A clean OpenAI fine-tuning dataset will generally work with Llama-compatible trainers without modification.</p>

<pre><code>{String.raw`{"messages": [
  {"role": "system", "content": "You are a concise code reviewer."},
  {"role": "user",   "content": "Review this Python function:\n\ndef square(n):\n  return n*n"},
  {"role": "assistant", "content": "Rename the parameter to 'n' and function to 'square'. No other issues."}
]}`}</code></pre>

<p>The practical differences that trip up cross-trainer datasets:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Special tokens.</strong> Some Llama fine-tuning frameworks expect <code>&lt;|begin_of_text|&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;|eot_id|&gt;</code> tokens to be absent from the JSONL — they are added by the tokenizer. Others require them. Check your trainer's documentation. DataPrep's Llama preset validates the <em>absence</em> of these tokens, which is the right default for Axolotl and torchtune.</li>
  <li><strong>System message.</strong> Not strictly required for Llama, but strongly recommended. Models trained without consistent system prompts generalise poorly.</li>
  <li><strong>Assistant turn last.</strong> Same requirement as OpenAI — the final message must be the one you want the model to learn to produce.</li>
</ul>

