<p>Multi-GPU training (2×A100) roughly halves wall-clock time but doubles cost — net effect near zero. Use multi-GPU when you need faster iteration, not for cost savings.</p>

<p>Spot instances on Vast.ai can be 40–60% cheaper than on-demand but may be interrupted. For training runs under 4 hours, spot is usually fine. For longer runs, on-demand is worth the premium to avoid checkpoint-resume complexity.</p>

<h2 id="when-to-use">When to Use Each</h2>

<p><strong>Choose OpenAI GPT-4.1 when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Speed of iteration matters more than training cost. OpenAI's API queues typically start within minutes.</li>
  <li>Your team has no GPU infrastructure experience and setting up CUDA environments would eat into product time.</li>
  <li>You need guaranteed uptime SLAs on the fine-tuned model for a customer-facing product.</li>
  <li>Your dataset is under 10M tokens — the OpenAI managed pipeline's overhead per-run is low at this scale.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Choose Llama 3.1 70B self-hosted when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Data privacy requires that training data never leaves your control. Healthcare, legal, and regulated financial data all fall here.</li>
  <li>You expect to run many fine-tuning iterations over time — the economics flip at scale.</li>
  <li>You want to own and version the fine-tuned weights, not just the checkpoint ID.</li>
  <li>You are comfortable with Linux, CUDA, and distributed training tooling, or can hire someone who is.</li>
  <li>You need inference cost of effectively zero at volume — your own GPU hardware runs at a fixed capital cost, not per-token.</li>
</ul>

